INSERT INTO `Animals` VALUES (18,'Chordata','','Mammalia','','Carnivora','','Canidae','','Canis','','lupus','','Dog','','','',NULL,'','','2017-12-10 12:14:46','anim1.jpg:','5',NULL,'2017-12-10 12:14:46',NULL,'yes',NULL,NULL),(19,'','','Mammalia','','Carnivora','','Felidae','','Felis','','catus','','Feral domestic cat, cat, pussy, Kat','','','','','','','2020-12-26 21:56:33','anim2.jpg:','1','added some local names','2017-12-10 12:19:03',NULL,'yes',NULL,NULL),(20,'','','Mammalia','','Rodentia','','Muridae','','Rattus','','norvegicus','','Brown rat (eng),Bruin rot (Afr)','','Similar to the House rat, but bulkier (150-300 g), sometimes up to 500 g) with relatively smaller ears, and a shorter tail (about 90% of head-body length) that is bicoloured (dark above and pale below) With a generous covering of bristly hairs. Body length 25 cm, tail about 22 cm long. Upperparts greyish-brown, flanks sometimes tinged with yellow, underparts paler with throat and chin being pale grey. Stronger and more aggressive than the House rat, which it tends to exclude.','Nocturnal and often territorial. Omnivorous and opportunistic. Rarely climbs, unlike House rat.','','','','2018-01-05 10:01:00','anim3.jpg:','5','','2018-01-05 10:00:11',3,'yes',NULL,NULL),(21,'','','Mammalia','','Rodentia','','Muridae','','Rattus','','rattus','','House rat, Black rat, Ship rat (Eng), Swart rot Skeepsrot Huis rot (Afr)','','A medium-sized rat, total length 34-40 cm, mass 105-184g, tall 18-21 cm long (longer than head and body combined, and uniformly dark, hairless and coarsely scaled). Fur harsh, black to blackish-brown or grayish-brown above, underparts vary from slate-grey tinged with sepia to white or yellowish\r\nExternally indistinguishable from the Asian house rat (Rattus tanezumi). The two species co-exist at several localities in north eastern South Africa. The introductory pathway of this newly recognised species in South Africa is not yet clear, but probably similar to that of the House rat. The House rat may be confused in coastal areas with the Brown rat (p. 25), which is bulkier with a bristly tail that is shorter than head-body length and bicoloured (black above, whitish below), and relatively smaller ears.','Nocturnal and predominantly herbivorous, but opportunistic feeder, taking a wide variety of small animal prey. An agile climber and swimmer','House rats can have marked impacts on plant communities through feeding (and also restrict regeneration by eating seeds and seedlings), and have contributed to range reduction or the local extinction of invertebrate and small vertebrate species. Like the House mouse, the environmental impact of this species is greatest on oceanic islands, where they have had catastrophic effects on populations \r\nof endemic birds and other fauna.','','','2018-01-05 07:34:45','anim5.jpg:anim4.jpg:','5','','2017-12-10 12:31:16',3,'yes',NULL,NULL),(22,'','','Mammalia','','Rodentia','','Sqiuridae','','Sqiurus','','carolinensis','','Grey squirrel(eng), grys eekhoring (Afr)','','A medium sized tree squirrel (body length 38-50 cm, tail 15-25 cm, mass 480 - 650g). Upperparts pale grey washed with cinnamon, underparts whitish.','Agile climber. \r\nRestricted to areas with sufficsent oak trees (Quercus robur) and/or pines (Pinus species), upon which it depends primarily for food. Avoids plantations and fynbos. Feeds mainly on acorns, pine nuts and other seeds, which it scatter-hoards during the summer. Also eats fruit, shoots, flowers, insects, fungi, eggs and rarely small vertebrates. Solitary, except for females with young. Active mostly in early mornings and late afternoons. During winter emerges from nest only every few days to feed.','','Terrestrial, tree-dwelling. Present only in parts of the Western Cape','Invasive','2018-01-05 06:34:33','anim6.jpg:','1','','2017-12-10 12:39:41',1,'yes',NULL,NULL),(23,'Vertebrata','','Mammalia','','Lagomorpha','','Leporidae','','Oryctolagus','','cuniculus','','European rabbit','','','','','','','2018-01-05 23:44:47','anim7.jpg:','1','','2017-12-10 12:44:19',3,'yes',NULL,NULL),(24,'','','Mammalia','','Artiodactyla','','Suidae','','Sus','','scrofa','','Feral domestic pig (Eng), Wilde vark (Afr)','','Medium large (body length 90-180 cm, shoulder height SS~1 10 cm, mass 60-200 kg), hoofed mammal with wedge-shaped head, pointed ears, flattened mobile snout and powerful body. Males generally larger than females, with four continually growing tusks. Body covered with a scant coat of coarse, bristly hair, adults often also have a scruffy mane. Tail not coiled, as in domestic pigs. Considerable variation in size and colour as a result of domestication and cross-breeding with Wild boars (the ancestral subspecies). Coat colour and patterns range from black through grey, brown, to \'whitish, often with spotted and belted combinations thereof. Their mobile snouts and sharp tusks are used to uproot prey or plant material.','Omnivorous and aggressive. Unlikely to be confused with indigenous bushpigs (Potamochoerus porcus) as these species seldom occur together','The natural range extends throughout Eurasia as far south-east as the Malaysian Peninsula, Sumatra and Java. Domesticated from Wild boars independently at least seven times, starting about 9 000 years ago. Transported by Neolithic migrants, and later by seafarers who released them at many settlements, or on islands as potential food for marooned sailors. Expansion into new areas by natural dispersal from wild populations or from free-ranging commercial farms. Most populations in the Western Cape originated from domestic pigs that strayed from farms, but two populations were deliberately introduced by the Department of Forestry into pine plantations (Tulbagh 1926 and Franschhoek, 1941) to control severe infestations of the . Pine emperor moth (Nudaure/ia cytherea cytherea). Domestic pigs released at Tulbagh were subsequently augmented by four Austrian Wild boars from Groote Schuur Zoo released in 1930, and genetic throwbacks bearing longitudinal back stripes typical of Wild boars are sometimes encountered. Small groups of feral pigs undoubtedly occur on some farms at other sites in South Africa, but usually do not persist, probably because of competitive exclusion by bushpigs and their susceptibility to swine fever. \r\nA small feral pig population originating from two Wild boars that escaped from a wildlife refuge has become established in the Pien\'aars River Valley near Pretoria, but long-term viability of this population remains uncertain. Impacts: included by the IUCN in the Top 100 Worst invasive Species. Cause extensive agricultural damage by feeding on crops, damaging pastures, preying on lambs, destroying infrastructure (especially fences), fouling water bodies, competing with livestock and soil erosion associated with their rooting and wallowing. Rooting and trampling by pigs alters soil characteristics and seed banks, and creates open patches colonised by alien plants. This, together with their habit of feeding on tubers, has led to a decline or local extinct','Terrestrial, cosmopolitan. in South Africa, significant feral populations are restricted to the Boland, Overberg and west coast of the Western Cape.','alien','2018-01-05 08:43:24','anim9.jpg:anim8.jpg:','5','','2018-01-05 08:40:41',NULL,'yes',NULL,NULL),(25,'','','Mammalia','','Artiodactyla','Peramelidae','Caprinae','','Capra','','hircus','','Feral goat (Eng), Wilde bok (Afr)','','Indistinguishable from domesticated goats, males 45-55 kg with beards, females 25-35 kg and beardless. Uni-coloured (mostly black, to various shades of brown) or multi-colored.','Wide habitat and dietary tolerances.','Domesticated in Iran highlands 10 000 years ago, subsequently spread throughout the world for meat and milk. Impacts: Included in IUCN Top 100 World\'s Worst Invasive Species. Degrade ecosystems through overgrazing and trampling, impacting fauna and flora. Size and impact of feral populations in South Africa largely undocumented and difficult to distinguish from those of free-ranging goats kept by pastoralists. Goat herbivory most damaging in Succulent Thicket (Eastern Cape), and still evident in areas now under conservation (such as Addo Elephant National Park).','Terrestrial, cosmopolitan','alien','2018-01-05 21:30:33','anim10.jpg:','5','','2018-01-05 08:44:42',NULL,'yes',NULL,NULL),(26,'','','Mammalia','','Artiodactyla','','Caprinae','','Hemitragus','','jemlahicus','','Himalayan tahr','','','',NULL,'','','2017-12-10 13:10:55','anim11.jpg:','5',NULL,'2017-12-10 13:10:55',NULL,'yes',NULL,NULL),(27,'','','Mammalia','','Perissodactyla','','Equidae','','Equus','','asinus','','Donkey','','','',NULL,'','','2017-12-10 13:16:37','anim12.jpg:','5',NULL,'2017-12-10 13:16:37',14,'yes',NULL,NULL),(28,'','','Mammalia','','Perissodactyla','','Equidae','','Equus','','ferus_caballus','','Feral horse','','','',NULL,'','','2017-12-10 14:06:26','anim13.jpg:','5',NULL,'2017-12-10 14:06:26',-3,'yes',NULL,NULL),(29,'','','Aves','','Galliformes','','Phasianidae','','Pavo','','cristatus','','Common peacock','','Large size, head plumes, blue body and massive \'eyed\' tail of male unmistakable. Female has whitish face, green neck, mottled upper breast and white\'lower breast and belly. Upperparts brownish-grey','Omnivorous. Largely sedentary, roosting communally in trees at night.','Native to lndian subcontinent. Popular ornamental bird with many small, semi~feral populations. impacts: On Heron Island, Australia, peacocks eat eggs and chicks of seabirds; unknown whether this occurs on Robben island.','Natural habitat near water sources in dry, deciduous forests. Local habitat alien tree infestations, wooded suburbia and farmsteads.','alien','2018-01-05 08:23:41','anim14.jpg:','5','','2017-12-10 14:16:20',NULL,'yes',NULL,NULL),(30,'','','Aves','','Passeriformes','','Fringillidae','','Fringilla','','coelebs','','Common chaffinch','','A small species; male combination of pinkish face and underparts, grey crown and nape, chestnut back and white shoulder patch and wing bar diagnostic. Female plainer, paler and\r\nbrowner, but has the conspicuous shoulder patch and wing bar.','A small species; male combination of pinkish face and underparts, grey crown and nape, chestnut back and white shoulder patch and wing bar diagnostic. Female plainer, paler and\r\nbrowner, but has the conspicuous shoulder patch and wing bar. Eats seeds and invertebrates.\r\nOccurs in pairs or small family groups; territorial when breeding in spring and early summer.','','Parks, gardens and alien woodlands.','alien','2018-01-05 08:20:45','anim15.jpg:','5','','2017-12-10 14:22:03',1,'yes',NULL,NULL),(31,'','','Aves','','Columbiformes','','Columbidae','','Columba','','livia','','Rock dove, Feral pigeon (Eng), Did (Afr)','','Highly variable in appearance due to hybridisation with both domestic pigeons and native Speckled pigeons (Columba guinea). Original wild type has iridescent purple-green head, neck and upper breast, pale blue-grey upperparts and a white band across the upper rump. Two black bars visible on folded wing. Underparts slate grey, legs and feet deep red.\r\nHybrids range from largely black to largely white.','Social, often in flocks of hundreds, regularly with Speckled pigeons. Breeds year-round. Nests mostly on ledges of buildings, rarely on cliffs; clutch size 1--2. Feeds mostly on seeds and grain, but much food derived from human discards, such as bread. Probably has closer contact with humans than any other bird species in South Africa','Native to parts of Europe, North Africa and South Asia. Many introductions documented worldwide, from southern Canada and the Americas east to New Zealand. Date of introduction in South Africa uncertain, but present by mid-18005. Now in towns and villages throughout the country, with lowest densities in arid north-west.\r\nImpacts:\r\nDiverse, including fouling of buildings, vehicles, grain stores, etc. with their droppings, and potential transmission of diseases, including histoplasmosis and possibly encephalitis. Regularly forages in animal feed lots, causing competition with agricultural sector, and significant consumers of grain stored for human consumption. in Cape Town consume 2-3 tonnes of stored grain daily. Also eat fresh green shoots of seed crops, placing them in further competition with agriculture. Control: No official control measures implemented to date, although losses from grain stores in Cape Town may lead to such measures being taken in future. However, given the species\' extensive South African range and regular supplementation of the population with escaped domestic birds, any control measures are likely to become ongoing operations. One of the major challenges to control efforts is its close association with humans.','Urban areas and cultivated fields','alien','2018-01-29 06:45:55','anim16.jpg:','1','','2018-01-05 08:29:52',NULL,'yes',NULL,NULL),(32,'','','Aves','','Passeriformes','','Corvidae','','Corvus','','splendens','','House crow','','The smallest crow in South Africa. Glossy black, with grey or grey-brown nape, mantle and breast. Bill, legs and feet black.','Gregarious, splits up into pairs when breeding. Roosts communally in large trees. Omnivorous, but eats mostly animal prey, especially eggs and nestlings of other birds. Also eats small mammals, fish, amphibians and invertebrates and steals food from other birds. Nests singly or in loose colonies.\r\nBuilds a substantial nest, usually in a tree, rarely on buildings. Lays 3-5 eggs; in Durban, average of 1.3 fledglings/nest.','Native to India and surrounds; widely introduced to tropical and subtropical mainland and island sites from eastern and southern Africa east to southern Australia. First recorded in South Africa in Durban between the late 1960s and early 1970s, possibly having spread from Zanzibar. Established in Cape Town in the early 1990s, perhaps from ship-assisted birds from Durban; founder population was fewer than 20 birds. Still confined to these two centres and Richards Bay. Impacts: Preys on eggs and nestlings of native birds, also eats small native animals. Mobs humans and pets. Potential air-strike hazard at Cape Town international Airport due to a nearby roost, which has now been removed. Occasionally destroys vegetable gardens in informal settlements. Vector for pathogens that cause cholera, typhoid, dysentery and salmonella poisoning','Towns and cities.','alien','2018-01-05 22:26:14','anim17.jpg:','5','made a change...not','2018-01-05 08:17:58',NULL,'yes',NULL,NULL),(33,'','','Aves','','Passeriformes','','Sturnidae','','Sturnus','','vulgarus','','Common starling European starling (Eng)','','Overall glossy black, with purple and green iridescence. Upperparts and underparts flecked buff and white, giving spotted appearance. Bill yellow, legs and feet red-brown.','Forages by day in small groups that coalesce at night to form large, communal roosts, often in reedbeds. Eats invertebrates, frogs, lizards, fruit, seeds, nectar and human discards. A hole nester, breeding singly or in loose colonies. Frequently nests in buildings, less often in natural cavities (sometimes evicting native species). Clutches contain up to six eggs.','A highly successful invasive, native to temperate Europe and western Asia. Two introductions in New York at end of 19th century resulted in colonization of most of North America and southern Canada. Within 25 years of arrival in California, one roost was estimated to contain five million birds. The South African founder population comprised 18 birds released by Cecil Rhodes at Groote-Schuur in Cape Town in 1889. By 1910 they had reached Stellenbosch and by 1922 had crossed the adjacent mountains. By the mid-1990s they had spread north through the western lowlands\r\nto Oranjemund, Namibia, and eastwards to southern KwaZulu-Natal. Since then the range has expanded northwards to central and eastern Free State, and first colonists have reached Gauteng and Mpumalanga, resulting in increasing overlap with distribution of the. closely related (alien) Common myna, which utilizes the same habitats and foods. Impacts: In south-eastern Australia, implicated in decreases in numbers of native species, especially parrots, probably due in part to competition for nest sites. A major pest of soft fruit crops in many parts of its non-native range Roof-nesting leads to fouling and introductions of ectoparasites, especially lice; implicated in the transmission of histoplasmosis.','Urban areas and agricultural lands.','Alien','2018-01-05 08:03:29','anim18.jpg:','5','','2018-01-05 07:59:28',14,'yes',NULL,NULL),(34,'','','Aves','','Anseriformes','','Anatidae','','Anas','','platyrhynchos','','Mallard','','','',NULL,'','','2017-12-10 14:51:07','anim19.jpg:','5',NULL,'2017-12-10 14:51:07',-1,'yes',NULL,NULL),(36,'','','Aves','','Passeriformes','','Passeridae','','Passer','','domesticus','','House sparrow','','','','','','','2018-01-08 03:00:22','anim21.jpg:anim20.jpg:','3','','2018-01-08 02:59:36',NULL,'yes',NULL,NULL),(37,'','','Teleostei','','Cyprinodontiformes','','Poeciliidae','','Gambusia','','affinis','','Mosquitofish','','','',NULL,'','','2017-12-11 12:24:12','anim22.jpg:','1',NULL,'2017-12-11 12:24:12',NULL,'yes',NULL,NULL),(38,'Arthropoda','','Insecta','','Dermaptera','','Anisolabididae','','Euborellia','','annulipes','','Ring-legged earwig','','Earwigs are a fairly small and uniform order of insects with about 2 200 species worldwide and 47 in South Africa. They are long and slender, typically brown and easily identified by the conspicuous forceps at the end of the abdomen. These are not venomous, but can inflict a painful pinch and are used to fold and unfold the intricate wings','Females care forthe eggs and first instar nymphs. Earwigs typically hide under stones, bark, leaf axils and other narrow spaces.','','','','2018-01-05 21:01:01','anim23.jpg:','5','','2018-01-05 07:54:33',NULL,'yes',NULL,NULL),(39,'','','Insecta',