a','','livia','','Rock dove, Feral pigeon','','','',NULL,'','','2017-12-10 14:29:28','anim16.jpg:','1',NULL,'2017-12-10 14:29:28',NULL,NULL,NULL),(109,25,'','','Mammalia','','Artiodactyla','','Caprinae','','Capra','','hircus','','Feral goat','','','',NULL,'','','2017-12-10 13:06:23','anim10.jpg:','5',NULL,'2017-12-10 13:06:23',NULL,NULL,NULL),(110,24,'','','Mammalia','','Artiodactyla','','Suidae','','Sus','','scrofa','','Feral domestic pig','','','','','','','2017-12-10 12:57:10','anim9.jpg:anim8.jpg::','5','','2017-12-10 12:53:24',NULL,NULL,NULL),(111,24,'','','Mammalia','','Artiodactyla','','Suidae','','Sus','','scrofa','','Feral domestic pig','','Medium large (body length 90-180 cm, shoulder height SS~1 10 cm, mass 60-200 kg), hoofed mammal with wedge-shaped head, pointed ears, flattened mobile snout and powerful body. Males generally larger than females, with four continually growing tusks. Body covered with a scant coat of coarse, bristly hair, adults often also have a scruffy mane. Tail not coiled, as in domestic pigs. Considerable variation in size and colour as a result of domestication and cross-breeding with Wild boars (the ancestral subspecies). Coat colour and patterns range from black through grey, brown, to \'whitish, often with spotted and belted combinations thereof. Their mobile snouts and sharp tusks are used to uproot prey or plant material.','Omnivorous and aggressive. Unlikely to be confused with indigenous bushpigs (Potamochoerus porcus) as these species seldom occur together','The natural range extends throughout Eurasia as far south-east as the Malaysian Peninsula, Sumatra and Java. Domesticated from Wild boars independently at least seven times, starting about 9 000 years ago. Transported by Neolithic migrants, and later by seafarers who released them at many settlements, or on islands as potential food for marooned sailors. Expansion into new areas by natural dispersal from wild populations or from free-ranging commercial farms. Most populations in the Western Cape originated from domestic pigs that strayed from farms, but two populations were deliberately introduced by the Department of Forestry into pine plantations (Tulbagh 1926 and Franschhoek, 1941) to control severe infestations of the . Pine emperor moth (Nudaure/ia cytherea cytherea). Domestic pigs released at Tulbagh were subsequently augmented by four Austrian Wild boars from Groote Schuur Zoo released in 1930, and genetic throwbacks bearing longitudinal back stripes typical of Wild boars are sometimes encountered. Small groups of feral pigs undoubtedly occur on some farms at other sites in South Africa, but usually do not persist, probably because of competitive exclusion by bushpigs and their susceptibility to swine fever. \r\nA small feral pig population originating from two Wild boars that escaped from a wildlife refuge has become established in the Pien\'aars River Valley near Pretoria, but long-term viability of this population remains uncertain. Impacts: included by the IUCN in the Top 100 Worst invasive Species. Cause extensive agricultural damage by feeding on crops, damaging pastures, preying on lambs, destroying infrastructure (especially fences), fouling water bodies, competing with livestock and soil erosion associated with their rooting and wallowing. Rooting and trampling by pigs alters soil characteristics and seed banks, and creates open patches colonised by alien plants. This, together with their habit of feeding on tubers, has led to a decline or local extinct','Terrestrial, cosmopolitan. in South Africa, significant feral populations are restricted to the Boland, Overberg and west coast of the Western Cape.','alien','2018-01-05 08:40:41','anim9.jpg:anim8.jpg:','1','','2017-12-10 12:57:10',NULL,NULL,NULL),(112,25,'','','Mammalia','','Artiodactyla','','Caprinae','','Capra','','hircus','','Feral goat','','Indistinguishable from domesticated goats, males 45-55 kg with beards, females 25-35 kg and beardless. Uni-coloured (mostly black, to various shades of brown) or multi-colored.','Wide habitat and dietary tolerances.','Domesticated in Iran highlands 10 000 years ago, subsequently spread throughout the world for meat and milk. Impacts: Included in IUCN Top 100 World\'s Worst Invasive Species. Degrade ecosystems through overgrazing and trampling, impacting fauna and flora. Size and impact of feral populations in South Africa largely undocumented and difficult to distinguish from those of free-ranging goats kept by pastoralists. Goat herbivory most damaging in Succulent Thicket (Eastern Cape), and still evident in areas now under conservation (such as Addo Elephant National Park).','Terrestrial, cosmopolitan','alien','2018-01-05 08:35:31','anim10.jpg:','1','','2017-12-10 13:06:23',NULL,NULL,NULL),(113,39,'','','lnsecta','','Dermaptera','','Labiduridae','','Labidura','','riparia','','Sand earwig, Striped earwig','','Earwigs are a fairly small and uniform order of insects with about 2 200 species worldwide and 47 in South Africa. They are long and slender, typically brown and easily identified by the conspicuous forceps at the end of the abdomen. These are not venomous, but can inflict a painful pinch and are used to fold and unfold the intricate wings.','Females care for the eggs and first instar nymphs. Earwigs typically hide under stones, bark, leaf axils and other narrow spaces.','','','','2018-01-05 07:52:59','anim24.jpg:','1','','2017-12-11 13:50:14',NULL,NULL,NULL),(114,40,'','','lnsecta','','Dermaptera','','Spongiphoridae','','Labia','','minor','','Lesser earwig','','Earwigs are a fairly small and uniform order of insects with about 2 200 species worldwide and 47 in South Africa. They are long and slender, typically brown and easily identified by the conspicuous forceps at the end of the abdomen. These are not venomous, but can inflict a painful pinch and are used to fold and unfold the intricate wings.','Females care for the eggs and first instar nymphs\r\n Earwigs typically hide under stones, bark, leaf axils and other narrow spaces.','','','','2018-01-05 07:50:05','anim25.jpg:','1','','2017-12-11 13:44:55',NULL,NULL,NULL),(115,20,'','','Mammalia','','Rodentia','','Muridae','','Rattus','','norvegicus','','Brown rat (eng),Bruin rot (Afr)','','Similar to the House rat, but bulkier (150-300 g), sometimes up to 500 g) with relatively smaller ears, and a shorter tail (about 90% of head-body length) that is bicoloured (dark above and pale below) With a generous covering of bristly hairs. Body length 25 cm, tail about 22 cm long. Upperparts greyish-brown, flanks sometimes tinged with yellow, underparts paler with throat and chin being pale grey. Stronger and more aggressive than the House rat, which it tends to exclude.','Nocturnal and often territorial. Omnivorous and opportunistic. Rarely climbs, unlike House rat.','','','','2018-01-05 06:44:32','anim3.jpg:','1','','2017-12-10 12:22:11',NULL,NULL,NULL),(116,20,'','','Mamalia','','Rodentia','','Muridae','','Rattus','','norvegicus','','Brown rat (eng),Bruin rot (Afr)','','Similar to the House rat, but bulkier (150-300 g), sometimes up to 500 g) with relatively smaller ears, and a shorter tail (about 90% of head-body length) that is bicoloured (dark above and pale below) With a generous covering of bristly hairs. Body length 25 cm, tail about 22 cm long. Upperparts greyish-brown, flanks sometimes tinged with yellow, underparts paler with throat and chin being pale grey. Stronger and more aggressive than the House rat, which it tends to exclude.','Nocturnal and often territorial. Omnivorous and opportunistic. Rarely climbs, unlike House rat.','','','','2018-01-05 10:00:11','anim3.jpg:','1','','2018-01-05 06:44:32',NULL,NULL,NULL),(117,52,'','','','','','','','','Pelecanus','','onocrotalus','','Great White Pelican','','','',NULL,'','','2017-12-16 20:19:18','anim37.png:','1',NULL,'2017-12-16 20:19:18',NULL,NULL,NULL),(118,39,'','','lnsecta','','Dermaptera','','Labiduridae','','Labidura','','riparia',''