INSERT INTO `Minerals` VALUES (1,'Amethyst','oxides','Trigonal','','SiO2 with Fe','7','2.65','Absent','Conchoidal','White','Vitreous','Absent','The name amethyst originally came from the Greek word ',NULL,'The amethyst is a purple or violet-blue gemstonethat belongs to the quartz family. Often the stone\'s purple colour appears in irregular or uneven patches. In other cases it only appears on  the outer edges of the crystals, with the remainder being transparent. to make these crystals more attractive in jewelery, they are sometimes gently heated to distribute the purple colour more evenly throughout the stone. this has to be done very carefully, because when heated to very high temperatures, amethysts lose their purple colour altogether and turn rich yellow as they turn into citrine quartz. The colour change is difficult to predict however and the stones can sometimes become brown or green.\r\nThe minerals that look most like amethysts are cordierites and violet scapolites, both of which belong to the silicates group. There is also a very rare purple variety in the corundum group known as \'oriental amethyst\'. Amethysts are often faked with a combination of glass and synthetic violet quartz.','Aside from their commercial popularity in jewelery, amethysts are worn by modern Christian bishops and cardinals as a reminder of Christ\'s passion and as a symbol of peace.\r\nIt is cited in the bible as one of the 12 stones adorning the breastplates of the high priests of Yahweh.','min1.jpg:min2.jpg:min3.jpg:min4.jpg:min5.jpg:','1','2016-06-10 19:57:52','The area with the greatest concentration of amethysts is the Rio Grande do Sul region of Brazil. Other significant deposits are found in Uruguay, India, Russia, Ceylon, Madagascar, Italy and the USA.','','2016-06-10 19:56:46',35,'yes',NULL,NULL),(2,'Andalusite','Silicates','Rhombic','','Al2SiO5','7.5','3.16 - 3.20','Prismatic and distinct','Irregular','White','','Yellowish-green','','','','','min6.jpg:','9','2018-01-16 09: